# Bug report

**What is the current behavior?**

When using shared modules with Webpack Module Federations, the worker chunk will contain references to shared contexts, but the worker runtime does not contain any information on how to load these contexts.

**If the current behavior is a bug, please provide the steps to reproduce.**

Simple reproduction repo: https://github.com/edusperoni/wmf-worker-bug

**What is the expected behavior?**

Worker runtime should contain the relevant information to load the modules, even if they're limited to eagerly loaded dependencies.

This "fixes" the issue by getting the needed information from the main chunk and adding them in the worker chunk 'consume-shared' section:

```
// lib/sharing/ConsumeSharedRuntimeModule.js
                 // Here we grab the "main" chunk, which contains all the needed information about eagerly shared modules
                 const extraChunk = [Array.from(compilation.chunks)[0]];
		// const extraChunk = [];
		for (const chunk of [...this.chunk.getAllAsyncChunks(),...extraChunk]) {
			const modules = chunkGraph.getChunkModulesIterableBySourceType(
				chunk,
				"consume-shared"
			);
			if (!modules) continue;
			addModules(modules, chunk, (chunkToModuleMapping[chunk.id] = []));
		}
		for (const chunk of [...this.chunk.getAllInitialChunks(),...extraChunk]) {
			const modules = chunkGraph.getChunkModulesIterableBySourceType(
				chunk,
				"consume-shared"
			);
			if (!modules) continue;
			addModules(modules, chunk, initialConsumes);
		}
```

I'm unfortunately not that well versed in the webpack source code, but it seems like we should be able to resolve this by passing the parent information related to shared modules to the worker to solve this issue.

Note: the above fix doesn't work if you have other chunks, as it only gets the information from the "main" chunk

